It was also in all likelihood a very lengthy as well as a costly undertaking. But the scribes fulfilled their orders exactly, sometimes even copying the same passage twice over, after a short interval, and certainly omitting nothing, for many entries occur in which the same subject is treated in nearly identical words, The work, in short, is a precise transcript of the papers and extracts which Gascoigne had been making between 1433, when, as he tells us (p. 129), he commenced his labours, and 1457, when, after Dec. 17, he writes that Pecok's books had been burnt at Carfaxâ€š Oxford, by Dr. Chandlerâ€š Warden of New College, and Chancellor of the Universityâ€š this being the last entry which is dated.

The Manuscript is in excellent preservation, the ink having hardly faded in any place, and the vellum being as clean as when it left the scribes' hands.
